1
00:00:00,200 --> 00:00:08,000
<i>Ten years ago, in the small East African country of Rwanda, 800,000 people were slaughtered by their own government.</i>

2
00:00:08,500 --> 00:00:12,091
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY, Military Ass't to Gen. Dallaire: 
This was ordinary men, women and children,

3
00:00:12,091 --> 00:00:15,475
and the only reason that they were killed was because they were Tutsi.

4
00:00:15,492 --> 00:00:18,018
<i>Virtually the entire world turned away</i>

5
00:00:18,100 --> 00:00:21,174
<i>and did almost nothing to stop the genocide.</i>

6
00:00:21,500 --> 00:00:24,826
MADELEINE ALBRIGHT, U.N. Ambassador: 
In retrospect, it all looks very clear.

7
00:00:24,900 --> 00:00:27,315
But at the time, what was happening in Rwanda, the situation was unclear.

8
00:00:28,334 --> 00:00:31,235
PHILIPPE GAILLARD, Red Cross: 
They cannot tell me that they didn't know.

9
00:00:31,344 --> 00:00:33,817
Everybody knew what was happening.

10
00:00:34,237 --> 00:00:40,437
<i>Tonight on FRONTLINE, the full story of perhaps 
the darkest and most brutal tragedy of our time.</i>

11
00:00:41,000 --> 00:00:43,004
<i>It is a story told by the victims</i>

12
00:00:44,000 --> 00:00:44,900
<i>and by the killers,</i>

13
00:00:46,000 --> 00:00:47,737
<i>by those who turned away</i>

14
00:00:48,454 --> 00:00:53,104
<i>and by those who stayed and tried desperately 
to save as many people as they could.</i>

15
00:00:53,730 --> 00:00:56,724
CARL WILKENS, Aid Worker, Adventist Church: 
By the time the genocide was over,

16
00:00:56,724 --> 00:00:58,629
I was so angry

17
00:00:59,555 --> 00:01:01,575
at America,

18
00:01:01,575 --> 00:01:03,500
America the beautiful, America the brave.

19
00:01:03,646 --> 00:01:06,613
<i>They are all still haunted by what happened--</i>

20
00:01:06,819 --> 00:01:11,500
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE, U.N. Force Commander, Rwanda: 
I was the commander, and hundreds of thousands of people died.

21
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:15,675
I can't find any solace in statements like, "I did my best."

22
00:01:16,000 --> 00:01:19,521
<i>--still haunted by the Ghosts of Rwanda.</i>

23
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
GHOSTS OF RWANDA

24
00:01:52,907 --> 00:01:55,801
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
Rwanda will never, ever leave me.

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:58,193
It's in the pores of my body.

26
00:01:59,551 --> 00:02:08,000
My soul is in those hills. My spirit is with the spirits of all those people who were slaughtered and killed that I know of.

27
00:02:09,800 --> 00:02:12,366
And lots of those eyes still haunt me,

28
00:02:12,625 --> 00:02:14,525
angry eyes or innocent eyes.

29
00:02:15,742 --> 00:02:17,292
No laughing eyes.

30
00:02:17,921 --> 00:02:24,421
But the worst eyes that haunt me are the eyes of those 
people who were totally bewildered.

31
00:02:25,592 --> 00:02:27,292
They're looking at me, with my blue beret,

32
00:02:28,005 --> 00:02:31,955
and they're saying, "What in the hell happened?

33
00:02:32,263 --> 00:02:34,513
"How come I'm dying here?"

34
00:02:38,536 --> 00:02:40,986
Those eyes dominated,

35
00:02:43,077 --> 00:02:44,527
and they're absolutely right.

36
00:02:46,403 --> 00:02:49,303
How come I failed?

37
00:02:52,089 --> 00:02:54,439
How come my mission failed?

38
00:02:55,005 --> 00:02:59,000
How come, as the commander, I did not convince,

39
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:00,676
I lost soldiers,

40
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:05,505
and 800,000 people died?

41
00:03:23,513 --> 00:03:31,033
August 1993

42
00:03:40,738 --> 00:03:46,038
<i>For General Romeo Dallaire, commander of the United Nations Assistance Mission for Rwanda,</i>

43
00:03:46,290 --> 00:03:48,590
<i>it was his first trip to Africa.</i>

44
00:03:55,563 --> 00:03:59,937
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
You know, the first breath of air of Africa--

45
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,050
oh, what a-- what a phenomenal experience!

46
00:04:05,290 --> 00:04:11,940
It's-- it felt like you were in another continent, that you were-- 
you were-- it was different.

47
00:04:17,559 --> 00:04:23,659
Felt a little nervousness, of course, you know, of the first shaking hands with --

48
00:04:23,768 --> 00:04:29,518
with those leaders and starting up the mission.

49
00:04:31,068 --> 00:04:36,818
<i>For Dallaire, a Canadian general who had never seen action, 
this was the command of a lifetime,</i>

50
00:04:37,072 --> 00:04:39,222
<i>a U.N. peacekeeping mission</i>

51
00:04:40,384 --> 00:04:42,534
<i>in the heart of Africa.</i>

52
00:04:45,023 --> 00:04:46,723
<i>His job seemed simple.</i>

53
00:04:47,373 --> 00:04:51,923
<i>He would enforce a peace agreement between 
the Rwandan government in Kigali</i>

54
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,926
<i>and a rebel army positioned behind a ceasefire line.</i>

55
00:05:00,201 --> 00:05:02,501
<i>The rebels were mostly Tutsis,</i>

56
00:05:02,595 --> 00:05:06,195
<i>an ethnic minority that had been persecuted for decades.</i>

57
00:05:08,274 --> 00:05:12,074
Gen. PAUL KAGAME, Cmndr, Rwandan Patriotic Front: 
Some of us had been refugees since 1959.

58
00:05:12,666 --> 00:05:20,016
And over the years, in the early '60s and '70s, there had been killings 
of Tutsis from different parts of Rwanda.

59
00:05:20,967 --> 00:05:25,917
So we mainly focused on the very fact that there was a 
need for change in the country

60
00:05:26,068 --> 00:05:29,018
and that these stateless people, ourselves,

61
00:05:29,679 --> 00:05:33,069
who were everywhere in the neighboring countries and beyond,

62
00:05:33,069 --> 00:05:35,319
needed to come back home.

63
00:05:40,395 --> 00:05:46,245
<i>The rebel threat had heightened tensions between Tutsis 
and the ethnic majority, the Hutus.</i>

64
00:05:48,547 --> 00:05:52,847
<i>The Hutus had ruled since independence from Belgium in the early '60s.</i>

65
00:05:59,570 --> 00:06:05,220
<i>Under the U.N.-backed peace accord, the Hutus would be 
forced to share power with the Tutsi rebels.</i>

66
00:06:10,227 --> 00:06:13,000
<i>But the peace process was already faltering,</i>

67
00:06:13,311 --> 00:06:18,161
<i>even as General Dallaire set up his command center in a rundown Kigali hotel.</i>

68
00:06:20,092 --> 00:06:28,892
<i>With only 2,500 lightly-armed troops, he was ill-prepared to enforce a 
fragile peace in a country he did not understand.</i>

69
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:34,846
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY, Military Ass't to Gen. Dallaire: 
We had very, very little information, knowledge of the background to Rwanda,

70
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:40,542
its history, its culture, the-- you know, what had taken place in the country 
since independence or even before independence,

71
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:45,445
and especially even in the last couple of years. 
So, we went in quite blind.

72
00:06:53,250 --> 00:06:59,100
<i>From the moment he arrived, someone was testing 
Dallaire's ability to keep the peace.</i>

73
00:07:00,192 --> 00:07:03,042
<i>There were mysterious riots and assassinations.</i>

74
00:07:05,021 --> 00:07:13,821
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: And-- and also, we were already getting all these stories 
about a third force, you know, of-- squadrons of killers.

75
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:20,000
And we couldn't confirm anything. 
We were just getting all that, you know, as rumors, innuendoes,

76
00:07:20,102 --> 00:07:26,292
and we couldn't cross-check the damn stuff 
because I was not allowed to have an intelligence capability.

77
00:07:27,312 --> 00:07:32,462
So all that sort of-- sort of came as a dark cloud.

78
00:07:34,880 --> 00:07:37,580
Ultimately, I-- I felt we could do it.

79
00:07:39,092 --> 00:07:43,942
But that is a bravado, I think, also, from my part.

80
00:07:45,995 --> 00:07:47,645
Nothing was going to stop me.

81
00:07:59,385 --> 00:07:51,885
Bit of innocence in there, eh?

82
00:07:54,044 --> 00:07:58,884
January 1994

83
00:08:02,725 --> 00:08:07,625
<i>Then, from inside the third force, an informant emerged.</i>

84
00:08:08,062 --> 00:08:14,212
<i>The informant revealed that a secretive group of Hutu extremists 
was plotting to derail the peace agreement</i>

85
00:08:14,337 --> 00:08:16,837
<i>and exterminate their enemies.</i>

86
00:08:17,087 --> 00:08:23,037
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
And he was within the higher structures of the MRND party,

87
00:08:23,256 --> 00:08:26,006
which was the hard-line party of the president.

88
00:08:26,693 --> 00:08:31,193
He said that he-- he simply wasn't going to continue to work in that atmosphere,

89
00:08:31,204 --> 00:08:33,954
that they were undermining the whole process

90
00:08:34,826 --> 00:08:43,800
and they were ultimately planning the evilest of deeds, of-- of attacking

91
00:08:43,900 --> 00:08:48,517
not only Tutsis but all the moderate Hutu leaders also.

92
00:08:52,488 --> 00:08:57,438
<i>The informant was a trainer for the Interahamwe, a paramilitary youth movement.</i>

93
00:08:58,038 --> 00:09:01,088
<i>He said they were planning to kill some of Dallaire's troops,</i>

94
00:09:01,581 --> 00:09:05,531
<i>Belgian soldiers, the backbone of the peacekeeping force.</i>

95
00:09:08,670 --> 00:09:12,511
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY: 
Jean-Pierre, the informant, said they felt that if the Belgians were killed,

96
00:09:12,609 --> 00:09:15,409
that Belgium and the U.N. would pack up and leave.

97
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,000
So already, the situation was changing, that somebody didn't want us there

98
00:09:20,289 --> 00:09:25,200
and that they were going to target us to-- to encourage us to go.

99
00:09:30,093 --> 00:09:35,343
<i>In an urgent cable to the U.N. leadership, 
Dallaire repeated the informant's warnings</i>

100
00:09:35,720 --> 00:09:39,420
<i>that there was a plan to exterminate all Tutsis in Kigali,</i>

101
00:09:39,814 --> 00:09:46,364
<i>that Belgian peacekeepers would also be killed in the belief that Belgium would then withdraw all its troops.</i>

102
00:09:51,774 --> 00:09:56,274
<i>Dallaire told New York he was going to raid the militia's arms caches.</i>

103
00:09:57,471 --> 00:10:05,071
<i>He signed off in his native French,
"Where there's a will, there's a way. Let's go."</i>

104
00:10:05,647 --> 00:10:10,047
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
I sent that, and then I went to bed and probably slept one of the best nights I had

105
00:10:10,077 --> 00:10:19,977
because I felt that, finally, we were going to-- we were going to take a certain level of control that would permit us to do so much more.

106
00:10:20,694 --> 00:10:26,444
<i>The cable arrived in New York at the United Nations' peacekeeping department, 
then run by Kofi Annan.</i>

107
00:10:31,075 --> 00:10:39,075
KOFI ANNAN, Head of Peacekeeping, U.N: 
And the fax came in. 
And General Dallaire had also been in touch on the phone with General Baril,

108
00:10:40,074 --> 00:10:44,874
and in fact, he has sent other messages where sometimes his question that,

109
00:10:44,900 --> 00:10:57,342
"Somebody came and gave me this information. I don't know how sincere it is, whether I'm being manipulated or not," because intelligence can also be used to manipulate you.

110
00:10:57,699 --> 00:11:04,849
<i>Annan was skeptical. In his response, he ordered Dallaire, 
first, not to take any action, and second,</i>

111
00:11:05,022 --> 00:11:08,072
<i>to share the informant's secrets with the Rwandan government,</i>

112
00:11:08,273 --> 00:11:12,923
<i>which he knew had strong ties to the Hutu extremists.</i>

113
00:11:14,347 --> 00:11:25,047
KOFI ANNAN: 
Why did we go that route? Often, sharing-- shining light on these things and telling those planning it at a governmental level

114
00:11:25,052 --> 00:11:34,052
that, "The international community knows what is being planned, we are monitoring, we are going to deal with you harshly and we know what you are up to"

115
00:11:35,061 --> 00:11:37,661
-- sometimes it's a very good deterrent.

116
00:11:39,172 --> 00:11:48,472
<i>Annan told Dallaire he was not to raid the arms caches 
and he must avoid any action that might cause U.N. troops to use force.</i>

117
00:11:50,899 --> 00:11:59,249
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
The big hammer at the end of the message that came to me within hours of my sending my information message

118
00:11:59,365 --> 00:12:04,830
was, "Stop, decease, and by the by, you're totally outside of your mandate."

119
00:12:05,077 --> 00:12:12,977
At that time, the whole philosophy was, "We don't want another Mogadishu, and so keep it tight."

120
00:12:18,000 --> 00:12:26,155
<i>Mogadishu. 
Three months earlier, when the Black Hawks were shot down in Somalia and 18 American soldiers died on a U.N. mission,</i>

121
00:12:26,764 --> 00:12:30,000
<i>it changed everything about Washington's commitment to peacekeeping,</i>

122
00:12:30,343 --> 00:12:32,393
<i>especially in Africa.</i>

123
00:12:38,134 --> 00:12:43,242
MICHAEL SHEEHAN, White House Liaison on Somalia: 
The Clinton administration was brought to its knees by the -- by the problem in Somalia.

124
00:12:43,397 --> 00:12:51,239
A secretary of defense was fired, a presidency was dramatically weakened. 
They were enormously criticized for this adventure in Somalia.

125
00:12:51,260 --> 00:13:00,640
And now you had another situation unfolding in Rwanda. 
And certainly, no one was clamoring for a re-intervention into the heart of Africa.

126
00:13:04,539 --> 00:13:07,739
March 1994

127
00:13:10,172 --> 00:13:15,822
<i>Despite the growing sense of danger, 
Kigali was teeming with thousands of Western expatriates</i>

128
00:13:18,074 --> 00:13:20,724
<i>-- diplomats, aid workers and their families.</i>

129
00:13:21,070 --> 00:13:26,620
<i>The official line from the U.N. and all their embassies was that Rwanda was still safe.</i>

130
00:13:28,006 --> 00:13:34,856
CARL WILKENS : 
It was strange because, on the one hand, here's little groups of eight U.N. soldiers,

131
00:13:34,956 --> 00:13:41,737
fully decked out, you know, with all of their gear and their machine guns and everything, patrolling the city-- of eight, you know?

132
00:13:41,769 --> 00:13:44,819
And we used to joke, you can't-- you can't spit without hitting a U.N. car.

133
00:13:44,924 --> 00:13:49,044
And so you got all this white vehicles, black "U.N." all over them,

134
00:13:49,100 --> 00:13:55,527
and-- and occasionally, you would see some white tanks or something. 
There was an incredible sense of security in that.

135
00:13:56,220 --> 00:13:59,300
And yet we also knew things were going to blow.

136
00:14:01,738 --> 00:14:06,788
<i>Hutu extremists were now confident the U.N. would not stand in their way.</i>

137
00:14:08,243 --> 00:14:15,143
<i>They imported thousands of machetes, prepared death lists and began targeting their political opponents.</i>

138
00:14:20,528 --> 00:14:27,481
MONIQUE MUJAWAMARIYA, Human Rights Activist: 
It became simply a nightmare for the Tutsis, for all of the members of the opposition parties,

139
00:14:27,481 --> 00:14:33,081
even if they were Hutu, and we lived through a series of political assassinations almost on a daily basis.

140
00:14:36,095 --> 00:14:45,595
Every day, every day God gave us, we had three, four, five dead bodies, people that we picked up on the streets every day.

141
00:14:50,626 --> 00:14:59,926
JOYCE LEADER, U.S. Embassy, Kigali: 
The people tried to tell us and tried to explain to us or help us understand, but we just-- maybe we just didn't get it.

142
00:15:00,562 --> 00:15:04,612
It was just very hard to conceive of something so awful

143
00:15:04,800 --> 00:15:09,100
actually being meticulously planned and carried out.

144
00:15:14,347 --> 00:15:18,447
April 6, 1994 

145
00:15:21,259 --> 00:15:29,009
<i>In central Kigali, a group of friends gathered for dinner 
at the home of a young American diplomat, Laura Lane.</i>

146
00:15:32,072 --> 00:15:34,457
LAURA LANE, U.S. Embassy, Kigali: 
We had a couple of friends over, and

147
00:15:35,718 --> 00:15:38,018
you know, I just-- we just sat down to dinner,

148
00:15:38,064 --> 00:15:41,964
and all of a sudden, there was a huge explosion. And I--

149
00:15:43,227 --> 00:15:50,727
I-- didn't instantly, you know, come to me what that was 
because I wasn't used to hearing those kinds of sounds.

150
00:15:53,293 --> 00:15:55,368
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
And then at 8:30, the first phone call came in,

151
00:15:56,298 --> 00:16:01,798
saying that there-- originally, the first phone call said 
that there had been a big explosion in Kanombe camp,

152
00:16:02,000 --> 00:16:07,038
which is just at the end of the runway of the airfield, the Kigali airfield,

153
00:16:07,869 --> 00:16:10,019
saying that it looked like an ammunition dump had exploded.

154
00:16:11,030 --> 00:16:16,025
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY: 
And it went from "There's been an explosion at the airport" to 
"We think it's the ammunition dump at Kanombe that's blown up"

155
00:16:16,371 --> 00:16:20,021
to "It's a plane that's crashed" to "It's the presidential plane that's crashed."

156
00:16:22,454 --> 00:16:27,104
<i>Someone had fired a missile that shot down the Hutu president's airplane.</i>

157
00:16:27,927 --> 00:16:33,277
<i>Even 10 years later, the responsibility for the attack remains a mystery.</i>

158
00:16:36,008 --> 00:16:38,974
Lt. Col. CHARLES VUCKOVIC, Defense Intelligence Agency: 
There are many theories as to who shot down the plane.

159
00:16:39,007 --> 00:16:42,081
I don't know if anybody has the answer to that.

160
00:16:42,292 --> 00:16:45,692
Was it Hutu extremists or was it Tutsi extremists?

161
00:16:45,700 --> 00:16:55,140
Was it done by the Tutsis as an excuse to begin the movement south by the RPF and take control of the country?

162
00:16:55,695 --> 00:16:56,580
Hard to say.

163
00:16:56,580 --> 00:17:01,695
Or was it used by the Hutu extremists to begin the genocide that took place?

164
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:03,760
I don't know the answer to that.

165



166
00:17:08,072 --> 00:17:13,522
<i>That night, U.N. commanders were summoned to a crisis meeting at Rwandan Army headquarters.</i>

167
00:17:14,522 --> 00:17:18,291
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY: 
We were heading through very darkened streets in Kigali, very quiet streets. There was no one--

168
00:17:18,291 --> 00:17:21,261
the streets were just empty. It was like a ghost town.

169



170
00:17:24,547 --> 00:17:29,947
They found a leading Hutu extremist, Colonel Theoneste Bagosora, in control.

171
00:17:34,147 --> 00:17:40,747
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
Colonel Bagosora was the chef de cabinet of the minister of national defense and a hard-line person

172
00:17:40,825 --> 00:17:44,625
-- in fact, considered even more than hard-line.

173
00:17:45,569 --> 00:17:47,009
He was chairing the meeting.

174
00:17:49,498 --> 00:17:53,948
<i>Bagosora had once vowed to launch an "apocalypse" against the Tutsis.</i>

175
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:02,030
<i>Dallaire insisted he step aside and hand power 
to the moderate acting prime minister Madame Agathe.</i>

176
00:18:04,329 --> 00:18:09,929
<i>Dallaire knew she would resist the extremists' power grab and appeal for calm.</i>

177
00:18:13,024 --> 00:18:19,724
Gen. ROMEO DALLAIRE: 
Bagosora kept saying that she's of no use and she never was able to garner her cabinet anyways, and--

178
00:18:21,006 --> 00:18:23,448
Maj. BRENT BEARDSLEY: 
An officer that was sitting next to me stunk a booze,

179
00:18:24,887 --> 00:18:28,187
started swearing in French underneath his breath about her

180
00:18:28,296 --> 00:18:30,186
and calling her various names and --

181
00:18:33,679 --> 00:18:35,579
so we were stalemated.

182
00:18:37,641 --> 00:18:39,741
April 7, 2:00 AM

183
00:18:40,027 --> 00:18:42,727
<i>Dallaire asked U.N. headquarters for guidance.</i>

184
00:18:42,801 --> 00:18:46,351
<i>They responded by tightening his rules of engagement.</i>

185
00:18:46,590 --> 00:18:53,009
<i>He was ordered not to intervene, and above all, to avoid armed conflict.</i>

186
00:18:56,007 --> 00:18:58,657
KOFI ANNAN: 
We were concerned, one,

187
00:18:58,707 --> 00:19:09,583
that Dallaire and his force didn't have the capacity and didn't -- to take on that sort of responsibility

188
00:19:09,583 --> 00:19:14,006
and that if they attempted to do it and any of 
the peacekeepers were killed, 

189
00:19:14,006 --> 00:19:20,256
we may see a repeat of Somalia and we may not even be able to offer any assistance.

190
00:19:33,737 --> 00:19:37,137
LAURA LANE: 
You heard gunshots. You heard screams. You heard--

191
00:19:38,141 --> 00:19:49,541
you heard just so much activity that you knew this was going to be, you know, an awful night. And in

