224
00:23:03,771 --> 00:23:07,021
<i>Rwandan troops stormed the prime minister's compound.</i>

225
00:23:07,772 --> 00:23:11,872
<i>The peacekeepers radioed for instructions from Dallaire's Ghanaian deputy.</i>

226
00:23:13,901 --> 00:23:16,743
Gen. HENRY ANYIDOHO, Deputy U.N. Cmndr, Rwanda: 
We were in communication with them all along, and

227
00:23:17,088 --> 00:23:22,008
it was not even rational for them to try to oppose them.

228
00:23:22,399 --> 00:23:25,205
The best they could do was to talk to them, to negotiate,

229
00:23:26,044 --> 00:23:30,244
to tell them, "Look, what you are about to do is wrong. You cannot do it."

230
00:23:32,800 --> 00:23:37,050
<i>At gunpoint, the U.N. troops surrendered their weapons to the Rwandans.</i>

231
00:23:38,057 --> 00:23:40,807
<i>The Ghanaian peacekeepers were soon released,</i>

232
00:23:40,830 --> 00:23:45,230
<i>but the 10 Belgian troops were taken hostage and led away.</i>

233
00:23:46,202 --> 00:23:48,081
Gen. HENRY ANYIDOHO: 
Their radios became silent.

234
00:23:48,943 --> 00:23:54,043
Then you suspected something had gone wrong 
because communication was utterly cut off.

235
00:23:55,261 --> 00:23:58,061
Then you sense the danger. Something must have happened.

236
00:24:01,064 --> 00:24:05,964
JOYCE LEADER: 
About another half hour later, we actually heard a scream and a shot

237
00:24:07,035 --> 00:24:12,335
and realized that it was the prime minister 
